postcontent:
Sig Sauer Specifications (1st pic is stock pic, other 2 are the actual pics of the gun for sale
•Item: 1911-22-B
•Caliber: .22 Long Rifle
•Action: Single action, blowback operated
•Trigger pull: 4.2-5.6 lbs. (advertised); 6-1/8 lbs. (measured)
•Length: 8.5"
•Width: 4"
•Height: 5.5"
•Barrel length: 5"
•Sight radius: 5.4"
•Weight w/magazine: 34 oz.
•Magazine capacity: 10 rounds
•Sights: Fixed, three dot, contrast sights (interchangeable front sights)
•Grips: Wood, stippled double diamond pattern
•Frame/slide finish: PTFE

Made in Germany, the blow-back operated SIG 1911-22 is an all metal pistol, except for its wood grips. The barrel, barrel bushing, hammer, slide stop and most internal parts are steel, while the slide, frame, thumb safety, grip safety, trigger and magazine are made of an unspecified, non-ferrous metal (probably aluminum alloy). The metal finish is a dull, matte black.

The SIG 1911-22 is obviously a well made pistol. Careful manufacture and assembly is evident and results in close tolerances. For example, there is almost no play in the gun's slide to frame fit.

The SIG 1911-22 operates exactly like a centerfire 1911 pistol and features the same control layout. Actually, the SIG 1911-22 represents a modern, "enhanced" 1911-A1 with an ambidextrous, extended thumb safety; radical beavertail grip safety; loop style burr hammer; long reach, skeletonized trigger adjustable for over-travel; grooved backstrap and low profile, three-dot, combat sights. It is very much in the style of SIG's "21st Century" .45 ACP 1911 pistols. Internally, SIG has added a magazine safety, drop safety and firing pin safety to the 1911-22. These are in addition to the usual 1911 hammer "quarter cock" safety, grip safety and thumb safety!

The high visibility front and rear sights are dovetail mounted in the round top slide. The rear sight, secured by a set screw, is drift adjustable for windage adjustment. A carrying case, Owner's Manual, gun lock, small tool set (including an open-end wrench, chamber brush and a couple of small Allen wrenches), are provided with the pistol. SIG is to be commended for including such a complete kit with their 1911-22 pistols. The only accessories most owners will ever need to buy is a spare magazine and, perhaps, a holster. The 1911-22 should fit in any holster intended for a full size 1911 pistol.

I purchased this as part of a 2 gun set with my Sig 1911 .45 Ultra, and I don't need another .22lr gun ( I already have the Sig P938-22).

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 4046 w/ 3 mags
postcontent:
This gun is in excellent condition, nearly flawless with minimal wear internally. Is an ex-police gun but appears to have been fired very little. Very high res pictures are available here: www.machzracing.com/4046

Comes with three 11 round mags and a S&W hard case. Has a smooth hammer, night sights though they're very dim, a single-double action trigger, no external safety, and has a mag safety so that it will not fire without a mag.

On the trigger, I call them single-double action as that is how they work but traditionally they're known as double action only. Pulling the trigger pulls back the hammer and fires just like a double action, difference is once fired you cannot pull the trigger again until the slide is cycled. For those used to single action or Glock type triggers (even though a Glock is single-double action) know that trigger pull on these guns is long and heavy, 10+ pounds. If you've ever fired a revolver in double action, that is how these feel. Many like that from a safety aspect since it has no external safety.

It is located in Howard though I frequently come to Wichita so can meet there. Will have a bill of sale. Only trade I'd be interested in would be for a Glock 43. Feel free to email with questions.

title: For Sale:  CLEARANCE SALE:  DWM Luger
postcontent: Let's kick it back to 1923 (OLD SCHOOL)! This is a DWM (Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken) manufactured pistol. She was made in 1923 and has no import marks. As far as I can tell she is all matching and she is in very good condition. She includes an original style magazine (not sure if it's original but it does have the wooden mag grip).CALIBER: 7.65x21 (.30 Luger). When the first Luger pistols were manufactured for Switzerland in 1900 they were in the .30 Luger cartridge (7.65 Parabellum). This is one of the first cartridges to use a bottleneck design which reduces the chances of jamming. The Soviets copied the design and made their own 7.62x25 bottleneck pistol cartridge, and the .357 Sig cartridge also copies the bottleneck design!9mm trivia I bet ya didn't know:PER WIKI: "In 1902 Luger presented the new round to the British Small Arms Committee as well as three prototype versions to the U.S. Army for testing at Springfield Arsenal in mid-1903. The Imperial German Navy adopted the cartridge in 1904 and in 1908 the German Army adopted it as well.[10] The ogive of the bullet was slightly redesigned in the 1910s in order to improve feeding."I bet you didn't know that the 9mm cartridge is over 100 years old and predates the .45ACP?This pistol was made in 1923 for the American market. It is stamped "GERMANY" on one side ~ don't mistake that for an import stamp because that's not the case.I digress - back the DWM Luger. I bought this pistol for myself and I've shot her few times. She's in awesome condition.  CHRISTMAS IS COMING and I can assure you that this would be an awesome gift!$999...(oh yeah - they don't make this anymore)

title: For Sale:  CLEARANCE SALE:  Walther P38 (cyq code)
postcontent: ld school, circa 1945! German WWII P38 for $875 (CYQcode)!This pistol came in on a trade a couple of months ago and we have marked her down for quick sale.This is the infamous Walther designed P38 that replaced the German P08 Luger just prior to WWII. The Walther P38 was cheaper to build, had fewer parts, and was much less complex than the Luger. This pistol was manufactured by Metallwarenfabrik Spreewerk GmbH in Czechoslovakia. Slave labor was used at this plant to produce firearms. By late 1944/early 1945 this was fairly common in Germany.This one was made in early 1945. I believe the Spreewerk plant was overrun by the Allies in April of 1945.NO IMPORT MARKS.ALL MATCHING.INCLUDES 2 MAGS.(9MM).If you need this (yes - you know who you are) then stop by the shop and take a look at her. I should put this one in my collection but I have have another P38 already. Christmas is coming and don't miss this opportunity for a collectible WWII firearm.
